2.1.6 Staff members making obversions

  • Who was the longest serving staff member(s) making observations?
    • How many years and at what location?
  • Did any staff member join again after they first performed the role?
In[]:
# Group by Observer and find the minimum and maximum year for each Observer
observer_years = data.groupby('Observer')['Year'].agg(['min', 'max'])

# Calculate the range of years for each Observer
observer_years['year range'] = observer_years['max'] - observer_years['min']

# Find the maximum range
max_range = observer_years['year range'].max()

# Find the Observers with the maximum range
longest_serving_observers = observer_years[observer_years['year range'] == max_range]

observer_locations = data.groupby('Observer')['Location'].agg(lambda x:x.value_counts().index[0])
longest_serving_observers = pd.merge(longest_serving_observers, observer_locations, left_index=True, right_index=True)
longest_serving_observers = longest_serving_observers.rename(columns={"min": "start", "max": "end"})

print('The longest serving staff members:')
longest_serving_observers

2.2 General Relationships (~2-5 marks each):

2.2.1 Is there a relationship between temperature and yield? (Consider in general is acceptable.)

In[]:
# Create a dictionary mapping Crop Type to color
color_map = {
    'Soy': (1.0, 0.4980392156862745, 0.054901960784313725),
    'Maize': (0.12156862745098039, 0.4666666666666667, 0.7058823529411765),
    'Wheat': (0.17254901960784313, 0.6274509803921569, 0.17254901960784313),
}
# Define marker shapes for irrigation categories
marker_map = {'Yes': 'o', 'No': 's'}

# Create an empty plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Create a scatter plot for each Crop Type and each Irrigation category
sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='Avg Min Temp *C', y='Yield', hue='Crop Type', style='Irrigation', palette=color_map, markers=marker_map, alpha=0.8)

# Add trend lines
for crop in data['Crop Type'].unique():
    for location in data['Irrigation'].unique():
        subset = data[(data['Crop Type'] == crop) & (data['Irrigation'] == location)]
        if not subset.empty:  # Ensure there is data for this combination
            z = np.polyfit(subset['Avg Min Temp *C'], subset['Yield'], 1)  # Fit a line
            p = np.poly1d(z)  # Create a function for the line
            plt.plot(subset['Avg Min Temp *C'], p(subset['Avg Min Temp *C']), color=color_map[crop], alpha=0.25)  # Plot the line

plt.title('Temperature vs Yield with Crop Type and Irrigation')

# Get the current axes
ax = plt.gca()

# Get the handles and labels for the figure
handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()

# Create a custom legend
ax.legend(handles=handles[1:], labels=labels[1:], title="Legend", title_fontsize='13', loc='upper right')
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1,1))
plt.grid(axis='y', zorder=10, alpha=0.4)
plt.show()

The "Temperature vs Yield with Crop Type and Irrigation" scatter plot reveals two trends for all crop types:

  • First, as the temperature increased, the yield from irrigated locations moderately increased.
  • In contrast, with higher temperatures, the yield from non-irrigated locations slightly decreased.

2.2.4 Is there a difference in yield trends (over time) at different locations?

In[]:
# Define marker shapes for each location
locations = data['Location'].unique()
markers = ['o', 's', '^']
marker_map = {location: marker for location, marker in zip(locations, markers)}

# Create an empty plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Create a scatter plot for each Crop Type and each Location
sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='Year', y='Yield', hue='Crop Type', style='Location', palette=color_map, markers=marker_map, alpha=0.8)

# Add trend lines
for crop in data['Crop Type'].unique():
    for location in data['Location'].unique():
        subset = data[(data['Crop Type'] == crop) & (data['Location'] == location)]
        if not subset.empty:  # Ensure there is data for this combination
            z = np.polyfit(subset['Year'], subset['Yield'], 1)  # Fit a line
            p = np.poly1d(z)  # Create a function for the line
            plt.plot(subset['Year'], p(subset['Year']), color=color_map[crop], alpha=0.25)  # Plot the line

plt.title('Year vs Yield with Crop Type and Location')

# Calculate the trendline
z = np.polyfit(data['Year'], data['Yield'], 1)
p = np.poly1d(z)
# Plot the trendline
plt.plot(data['Year'], p(data['Year']), "r--", alpha=0.4)

# Get the current axes
ax = plt.gca()

# Get the handles and labels for the figure
handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()

# Create a custom legend
legend = ax.legend(handles=handles[1:], labels=labels[1:], title="Legend", title_fontsize='13', loc='upper right')

# Put a legend to the right of the current axis
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)
plt.grid(axis='y', zorder=10, alpha=0.2)
plt.yticks(np.arange(700, 1900, 100))

plt.show()

The 'Year vs Yield with Crop Type and Location' scatter plot reveals three trends:

  1. As the years progressed, crop yields in irrigated locations, 'Emilyland' and 'East Xavierport', increased.
  2. In contrast, in non-irrigated location, 'North Daniel', saw a slight decrease in crop yield over the same period.
  3. The average trend line (red line) indicates a decline due to reduced production of the high-yield crop which is soy.
